 262‚Üí
 263‚ÜíIntegration Strategy: Clerk + Hasura in Next.js
 264‚Üí
 265‚Üí1. Authentication Middleware
 266‚Üí   Use Clerk‚Äôs Next.js middleware to validate JWTs and protect routes. For example, in middleware.ts at the project root include Clerk‚Äôs middleware and route matcher
 267‚Üí   clerk.com
 268‚Üí   :
 269‚Üí   import { clerkMiddleware } from '@clerk/nextjs/server';
 270‚Üí
 271‚Üíexport default clerkMiddleware();
 272‚Üíexport const config = { matcher: ['/((?!\_next|[^?]_\\.(?:html?|css|js(?!on)|...))._)','/(api|trpc)(._)'] };
 273‚ÜíThis ensures every request passes through Clerk. To require authentication on specific routes, use auth.protect() or check auth().userId within middleware
 274‚Üíclerk.com
 275‚Üí. For example:
 276‚Üíimport { clerkMiddleware, createRouteMatcher } from '@clerk/nextjs/server';
 277‚Üíconst protectedRoutes = createRouteMatcher(['/app/(._)', '/admin/(.\*)']);
 278‚Üíexport default clerkMiddleware(async ({ auth }, req) => {
 279‚Üíif (protectedRoutes(req)) {
 280‚Üíawait auth.protect(); // redirects to sign-in if no session
 281‚Üí}
 282‚Üí});
 283‚ÜíWithin route handlers or API routes, use await auth() to get the current session. For example, in a Next.js App Router handler:
 284‚Üíimport { auth } from '@clerk/nextjs/server';
 285‚Üíexport async function POST(request) {
 286‚Üíconst { userId, sessionId } = await auth();
 287‚Üíif (!userId) return new Response('Unauthorized', { status: 401 });
 288‚Üí// proceed with userId...
 289‚Üí} 2. Hasura Claims & Token Passing
 290‚ÜíConfigure Clerk‚Äôs Hasura JWT template so that each issued token contains the Hasura namespace with session variables (like x-hasura-user-id, x-hasura-default-role, x-hasura-allowed-roles). In the Clerk Dashboard under JWT Templates, create or use the Hasura template ‚Äì it pre-populates the required claims
 291‚Üíclerk.com
 292‚Üí. For dynamic roles, set the JWT claim to use {{user.publicMetadata.role}}. For example:
 293‚Üí{
 294‚Üí"claims": {
 295‚Üí"jwt": {
 296‚Üí"hasura.io": {
 297‚Üí"x-hasura-user-id": "{{user.id}}",
 298‚Üí"x-hasura-default-role": "{{user.publicMetadata.role}}",
 299‚Üí"x-hasura-allowed-roles": ["{{user.publicMetadata.role}}", "anonymous"]
 300‚Üí}
 301‚Üí}
 302‚Üí}
 303‚Üí}
 304‚ÜíConfigure Hasura‚Äôs JWT secret to use Clerk‚Äôs JWKS endpoint (e.g. https://<YOUR_CLERK_DOMAIN>/.well-known/jwks.json)
 305‚Üíclerk.com
 306‚Üí. When calling Hasura, include the Clerk JWT. For client-side GraphQL calls, use Clerk‚Äôs useAuth().getToken and attach it as a Bearer token
 307‚Üíclerk.com
 308‚Üí. For example, using Fetch:
 309‚Üíconst { getToken } = useAuth();
 310‚Üíconst token = await getToken({ template: 'hasura' });
 311‚Üíawait fetch(process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_HASURA_URL, {
 312‚Üímethod: 'POST',
 313‚Üíheaders: {
 314‚Üí'Content-Type': 'application/json',
 315‚Üí'Authorization': `Bearer ${token}`
 316‚Üí},
 317‚Üíbody: JSON.stringify({ query: MY_GRAPHQL_QUERY })
 318‚Üí});
 319‚ÜíOn the server side (e.g. in a Next.js route), you can also generate the JWT via Clerk‚Äôs Backend SDK. For example, in an App Router API route:
 320‚Üíimport { auth, clerkClient } from '@clerk/nextjs/server';
 321‚Üíexport async function POST(req) {
 322‚Üíconst { userId, sessionId } = await auth();
 323‚Üíif (!userId) return new Response('Unauthorized', { status: 401 });
 324‚Üíconst client = await clerkClient();
 325‚Üíconst { jwt: token } = await client.sessions.getToken(sessionId, 'hasura');
 326‚Üí// Call Hasura with the token
 327‚Üí}
 328‚ÜíThis pattern (using auth() and client.sessions.getToken) is shown in Clerk‚Äôs docs
 329‚Üíclerk.com
 330‚Üí. You may also inject Hasura headers directly: read auth() or currentUser() to get userId and user.publicMetadata.role, then include them as custom headers (x-hasura-user-id, etc.) in your Hasura request if not using JWT mode. 3. User Sync to Hasura
 331‚ÜíWebhooks for User Events
 332‚ÜíSet up a secure webhook endpoint (e.g. /api/webhooks/clerk) to receive Clerk events. In Clerk Dashboard > Webhooks, add a new endpoint and subscribe to events like user.created, user.updated, and organization.membership.created. Verify incoming requests via Svix signature (using svix-signature header and Clerk‚Äôs signing secret). For example:
 333‚Üíimport { verifyClerkWebhookSignature } from '@clerk/clerk-sdk-node';
 334‚Üí
 335‚Üíexport async function POST(req: NextRequest) {
 336‚Üíconst payload = await req.json();
 337‚Üíconst sig = req.headers.get('svix-signature')!;
 338‚Üíif (!verifyClerkWebhookSignature(sig, process.env.CLERK_WEBHOOK_SECRET!, JSON.stringify(payload))) {
 339‚Üíreturn new Response('Bad signature', { status: 400 });
 340‚Üí}
 341‚Üí// Process payload.data based on event type...
 342‚Üí}
 343‚ÜíHandle relevant events: when a new user signs up (user.created) or when an invited user joins (organization.membership.created ‚Äì triggered when a user accepts an org invite
 344‚Üílinkedin.com
 345‚Üí), extract the user‚Äôs Clerk ID, name, email, role, image, and any custom flags (publicMetadata.is_staff, etc.). Then upsert into your Hasura users table and maintain the many-to-many user_roles link. For example, using Hasura‚Äôs GraphQL API:
 346‚Üí// Pseudocode for inserting/updating user:
 347‚Üíconst mutation = `mutation UpsertUser($user: users_insert_input!) {
 348‚Üí    insert_users_one(object: $user, on_conflict: {
 349‚Üí      constraint: users_pkey, update_columns: [first_name, last_name, email, image, role, is_staff]
 350‚Üí    }) { id }
 351‚Üí  }`;
 352‚Üíconst variables = {
 353‚Üíuser: {
 354‚Üíid: data.id,
 355‚Üífirst_name: data.first_name,
 356‚Üílast_name: data.last_name,
 357‚Üíemail: data.email_addresses[0]?.email_address || null,
 358‚Üíimage: data.image_url || null,
 359‚Üírole: data.public_metadata?.role || 'user',
 360‚Üíis_staff: data.public_metadata?.is_staff || false
 361‚Üí}
 362‚Üí};
 363‚Üíawait fetch(process.env.HASURA_URL, { headers: { 'x-hasura-admin-secret': HASURA_ADMIN_SECRET }, method: 'POST', body: JSON.stringify({ query: mutation, variables }) });
 364‚ÜíThen update the join table: e.g. ensure a corresponding row in user_roles links this user to the role(s) in roles table. (You may need to insert into roles table first if using non-enum roles.) Use GraphQL mutations (such as insert_user_roles) with on_conflict to avoid duplicates. Repeat for role changes in later steps.
 365‚ÜíEnsure Consistent Role Fields
 366‚ÜíIf your users table has a role enum column, map publicMetadata.role to it. On any webhook indicating a metadata change (e.g. user.updated), update the user‚Äôs role in Hasura and adjust user_roles. For example:
 367‚Üíconst mutation = `mutation ($id: uuid!, $role: roles_enum!) {
 368‚Üí    update_users_by_pk(pk_columns: {id: $id}, _set: {role: $role}) { id }
 369‚Üí  }`;
 370‚Üíawait fetch(HASURA_URL, { headers: {...}, method: 'POST', body: JSON.stringify({ query: mutation, variables: { id: data.id, role: data.public_metadata.role } }) });
 371‚ÜíLog all sync operations and handle errors gracefully (retry on transient failures) for auditability. 4. Invitation Management
 372‚ÜíLeverage Clerk Organizations for invites. Restrict invites to admin roles (e.g. Developers/Admins/Managers). In the admin UI, use Clerk‚Äôs useOrganization() hook (client-side) to invite and list pending invitations
 373‚Üíclerk.com
 374‚Üíclerk.com
 375‚Üí. For example, an Invite Member form:
 376‚Üí'use client';
 377‚Üíimport { useOrganization } from '@clerk/nextjs';
 378‚Üíexport function InviteMemberForm() {
 379‚Üíconst { organization, invitations } = useOrganization();
 380‚Üí// form state...
 381‚Üíasync function onSubmit(e) {
 382‚Üíe.preventDefault();
 383‚Üíawait organization.inviteMember({ emailAddress: email, role: selectedRole });
 384‚Üíawait invitations?.revalidate?.(); // refresh invite list
 385‚Üí}
 386‚Üíreturn (
 387‚Üí
 388‚Üí<form onSubmit={onSubmit}>
 389‚Üí<input name="email" value={email} onChange=... placeholder="Email" />
 390‚Üí{/_ Role selector omitted for brevity _/}
 391‚Üí<button type="submit">Invite</button>
