 424‚Üíclerk.com
 425‚Üí. To ‚Äúresend‚Äù an invite, you can revoke and re-invite the same email. After an invite is accepted, Clerk will either redirect the user to sign-up/sign-in (with a \_\_clerk_ticket token in URL)
 426‚Üíclerk.com
 427‚Üí. Once the user joins the organization, Clerk emits organization.membership.created. The webhook handler from step 3 will catch this and sync the new member into Hasura. You can also poll Clerk‚Äôs membership list via organization.getMemberships() if needed, but webhooks are more robust for syncing. 5. Role Management
 428‚ÜíBuild an admin interface to manage user roles. For each user, allow updating their publicMetadata.role via Clerk‚Äôs Backend SDK and reflecting that change in Hasura. In Next.js (server), use clerkClient.users.updateUser:
 429‚Üíconst client = await clerkClient();
 430‚Üíawait client.users.updateUser(userId, { publicMetadata: { role: newRole } });
 431‚ÜíThen issue a Hasura mutation to update users.role and adjust user_roles. For example:
 432‚Üímutation UpdateRole($id: uuid!, $role: roles_enum!) {
 433‚Üí  update_users_by_pk(pk_columns: {id: $id}, _set: {role: $role}) { id }
 434‚Üí  delete_user_roles(where: {user_id: {_eq: $id}}) { affected_rows }
 435‚Üí  insert_user_roles(objects: [{user_id: $id, role_id: $roleId}]) { affected_rows }
 436‚Üí}
 437‚ÜíReplace $roleId by looking up the corresponding role record. Run these mutations via Hasura‚Äôs API. Clerk‚Äôs JWT claims will update on next token retrieval, so new tokens will carry the updated role. You may prompt users to re-login or simply rely on token refreshing (Clerk tokens are short-lived and fetched per request
 438‚Üíclerk.com
 439‚Üí). Ensure the UI and server enforce permissions: only users with admin-level roles (e.g. ‚ÄúDeveloper‚Äù, ‚ÄúManager‚Äù, ‚ÄúAdmin‚Äù) can use this interface. In Next.js route handlers or page loaders, check the current user‚Äôs role (from currentUser().public_metadata.role or via a roles query) and return a 403 if unauthorized.
 440‚Üí6. User Deactivation
 441‚ÜíProvide a ‚ÄúDeactivate‚Äù action for admins. When triggered, call Clerk‚Äôs deleteUser() API and mark the user inactive in Hasura. For example:
 442‚Üíconst client = await clerkClient();
 443‚Üíawait client.users.deleteUser(userId);
 444‚Üíawait fetch(HASURA_URL, {
 445‚Üí  headers: { 'x-hasura-admin-secret': HASURA_ADMIN_SECRET },
 446‚Üí  method: 'POST',
 447‚Üí  body: JSON.stringify({
 448‚Üí    query: `
 449‚Üí      mutation Deactivate($id: uuid!) {
 450‚Üíupdate_users_by_pk(pk_columns: {id: $id}, \_set: {active: false}) { id }
 451‚Üí}`,
 452‚Üívariables: { id: userId }
 453‚Üí})
 454‚Üí});
 455‚ÜíHere, users.active is a boolean flag. Do not delete the row, only set active=false for auditing. Deletion of the Clerk account will also revoke all sessions. Note: Clerk will emit a user.deleted webhook event (you may choose to ignore it or use it to double-check the flag). The key is to prevent the user from signing in (since the account is gone) while preserving their history in the DB. 7. Security & Error Handling
 456‚ÜíAccess Control: Wrap all admin pages and API routes with role checks. On the client, use Clerk hooks (e.g. useUser()) to hide admin UIs. On the server, use await auth() or await currentUser() and verify publicMetadata.role. For example:
 457‚Üíconst { userId } = await auth();
 458‚Üíconst user = await clerkClient().users.getUser(userId);
 459‚Üíconst role = user.publicMetadata.role;
 460‚Üíif (!['Admin','Manager','Developer'].includes(role)) {
 461‚Üíreturn new Response('Forbidden', { status: 403 });
 462‚Üí}
 463‚ÜíClerk‚Äôs own helpers support guarding routes as well
 464‚Üíclerk.com
 465‚Üí.
 466‚ÜíError Handling: In webhook and API code, use try/catch around network calls and mutations. Log errors to a monitoring system or console. For example, if a Hasura sync fails, catch it and log details to help debugging. Return appropriate HTTP status codes on failure. Clerk webhooks will retry automatically on 5xx errors, so ensure your webhook handler returns 500 on transient issues.
 467‚ÜíLogging: Add logs for key actions (invite sent, user synced, role change, deactivation). In Next.js, consider a logging library or just console.error. Store logs externally if audit trails are needed. 8. UI Components & Clerk Elements
 468‚ÜíAdmin Pages: Use Next.js App Router with server and client components. Wrap the app in <ClerkProvider> so you can use Clerk hooks. Protect /admin/\* routes via middleware or page logic.
 469‚ÜíInvite Member Form: (Client-side component) Use useOrganization() as shown above to invite by email and role
 470‚Üíclerk.com
 471‚Üí. Include a select/dropdown for roles (fetched via organization.getRoles()).
 472‚ÜíInvitation List Table: (Client) Display pending invitations with Revoke buttons
 473‚Üíclerk.com
 474‚Üí. Include pagination if needed (invitations.fetchNext(), etc. as in [38]).
 475‚ÜíUser List: (Either fetch from Hasura or use Clerk‚Äôs Admin UI API) Show all users, their roles, and active status. For each user, include:
 476‚ÜíA Role dropdown (for admin to change role).
 477‚ÜíA Deactivate button. Disable or hide these controls if the current user lacks permission.
 478‚ÜíUseUser/useAuth Hooks: In client components (like forms), use useUser() (to get details of the logged-in user) and useAuth() (to call getToken) as needed.
 479‚ÜíServer-side Fetching: To display Hasura data (users, roles), you may write Next.js server components or route handlers that query Hasura. In those, attach the Clerk JWT (via getToken) as auth, or use an admin secret if server-side trust is acceptable.
 480‚ÜíClerk Elements: Leverage Clerk‚Äôs pre-built components for login/logout (e.g. <SignIn/>, <UserButton/>) in the app as needed. Use Clerk‚Äôs organization UI if you prefer not to custom-build all flows; but the above custom components are recommended for full control and integration with Hasura.
 481‚ÜíAll implementations should maintain clear separation of concerns (authentication, database sync, UI). By following Clerk‚Äôs middleware and API patterns
 482‚Üíclerk.com
 483‚Üíclerk.com
 484‚Üí, and using webhooks for asynchronous sync, the system will remain secure and consistent. Sources: Clerk‚Äôs documentation on Hasura integration and middleware
